Relationship between surface tension of liquid with temperature is given by the equation

quest_title: When an ideal diatomic gas is heated at constant pressure, the fraction of heat energy supplied which increases the internal energy of the gas is
explanation_txt:
\(Q = nC \Delta T\)

\(\because P = \) constant,

\(Q = nC_p \Delta T\)

For diatomic gas, \(C_p = \cfrac{7R}{2}\)

\(Q = n \times \cfrac{7R}{2} \times T\)

And,

\(\Delta U = nC_v \Delta T = n \times \cfrac{5R}{2} \times T\)

\(\therefore \cfrac{\Delta U}{Q} = \cfrac{n \times \cfrac{5R}{2} \times T}{n \times \cfrac{7R}{2} \times T} = \cfrac{5}{7}\)

explanation_txt:
The centripetal force \(F = \cfrac { m v ^ { 2 } } { r } \Rightarrow r = \cfrac { m v ^ { 2 } } { F }\)

\(\therefore r \propto v ^ { 2 } \text { or } v \propto \sqrt { r }\) (if m and F are constant)

\(\Rightarrow \cfrac { v _ { 1 } } { v _ { 2 } } = \sqrt { \cfrac { r _ { 1 } } { r _ { 2 } } } = \sqrt { \cfrac { 1 } { 2 } }\)
